    <abstract id="aspace_54240bba550cc87c6cbc8617d80a8b7c">This collection contains student handbooks from schools within New York University dating from 1854 to 2009. The early handbooks cover the university in its entirety, but later are often school- and program-specific.</abstract>
    <langmaterial id="aspace_089f99e962f657acdabe9191273ccba2">Materials in English.</langmaterial>
  </did>
  <accessrestrict id="aspace_9eda635508885cfabe65b9b40bded8f9">
    <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
<p>Materials are open without restrictions.</p>  </accessrestrict>
  <arrangement id="aspace_250d2dfeb88bf4de384210e13b0e0ff2">
    <head>Arrangement</head>
<p>Items are arranged at the folder level. The handbooks are arranged first by their Record Group (based on school or program) and then chronologically within that RG.</p>  </arrangement>
  <prefercite id="aspace_7c77a880f81ab00cfbe1deb713bfb2ce">
    <head>Preferred Citation</head>
<p>Published citations should take the following form: Identification of item, date; New York University Archives Collection of Student Handbooks; MC 301; box number; folder number; New York University Archives, New York University Libraries.</p>  </prefercite>
  <scopecontent id="aspace_e8bd40b76bb328775f2d362535009031">
    <head>Scope and Contents</head>
<p>This collection contains student handbooks dating from 1854 to 2009 generated by New York University and its component schools. These handbooks gave students information on services provided by the school, resources for student life, and student activities at NYU. It also contains guidebooks for financial aid, dormitories, and conducting research.</p>  </scopecontent>
  <userestrict id="aspace_6d70be8b9e083945f524e6f44e8d2955">
    <head>Conditions Governing Use</head>
<p>This collection is protected by copyright and/or related rights. You are free to use materials in the collection in any way that is permitted by the copyright and related rights legislation that applies to your use. For other uses you need to obtain permission from the rights-holder(s).</p>  </userestrict>
  <bioghist id="aspace_9519d73d773672fb6a960361e2ae7a01">
    <head>Historical Note</head>
<p>The earliest handbooks from the collection date from the 1850s and touch upon subjects such as student behavior and locations of university buildings. Later handbooks were published for specific schools and specific programs within these schools.</p>  </bioghist>
  <acqinfo id="aspace_2dcb9f9d34362873752cb23714aa01b6">
    <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
<p>Materials found in collection; provenance is unknown for the bulk of materials. 1928-1928 edition of The Waverly is the gift of Mark A. Goldstein, 2018. An accretion was added in 2022.</p>  </acqinfo>
  <processinfo id="aspace_1ee86b32a1d1b7528a33a33789d2555f">
    <head>Processing Information</head>
<p>Information about decisions regarding arrangement, description, and physical interventions taken on this collection prior to 2026 are unknown.</p><p>In 2025-2026, student handbooks dated from 1897-1916 were rehoused by conservators for improved preservation and access. These materials had previously been housed in Box 1 and were rehoused in Box 25.</p>  </processinfo>
